A First Step in Understanding Logistic Regression Applications in Rare Events

Author

Steven Wong

Published

December 6, 2025

Introduction

Logistic regression is one of the most widely used statistical models for binary outcomes, especially in clinical and public-health research. In this project we apply logistic regression to a Kaggle stroke dataset to explore how well common risk factors predict stroke, and to compare three related models:

  • Standard logistic regression
  • Firthâs penalized logistic regression
  • FLIC (Firth with intercept correction)

We also briefly review the history of the logistic function, its role in odds and log-odds modelling, and why it is a natural choice for stroke prediction.

Brief background

The logistic function originated in population-growth modelling. Verhulst proposed the differential equation which led to the logistic function

an S-shaped function bounded between 0 and 1.

Over time, the logistic function was adopted in toxicology, psychology, econometrics, and then generalized into what we now call logistic regression: a regression model that links predictors to the log-odds of a binary response. With modern computing and software, logistic regression has become a standard tool in medicine, finance, and social science.

Logistic regression in stroke research (examples)

Many stroke-related studies have used logistic regression to:

  • Identify inflammatory markers associated with acute ischemic stroke outcomes
  • Rank vascular risk factors for improved risk calculators
  • Study how comorbidities such as hyperlipidemia or diabetes influence stroke severity and mortality
  • Evaluate lifestyle factors (e.g., smoking, diet, physical activity) in large observational cohorts

These applications motivate our choice of logistic regression for the Kaggle stroke dataset and provide clinical context for interpreting model coefficients and predictive performance.

A common standard logistic form sets (L=1), yielding a function that maps any real-valued input to a probability in (0, 1).

In the stroke context, each point on the curve represents a patient with certain risk-factor values (age, blood pressure, glucose, etc.), and the logistic curve maps those risk factors to an estimated stroke probability. A threshold (often 0.5, but not always optimal) converts this probability into a predicted class (âstrokeâ vs âno strokeâ).

Data and analysis

Data acquisition

We use the public stroke.csv dataset from Kaggle, which includes variables such as:

  • age
  • gender
  • hypertension
  • heart_disease
  • ever_married
  • work_type
  • Residence_type
  • avg_glucose_level
  • bmi
  • smoking_status
  • stroke (0 = no stroke, 1 = stroke)

Data cleaning

We recode missing or ambiguous values, convert appropriate columns to factors, and drop the id column. BMI and glucose are converted to numeric and rounded for convenience.

Model specification

We use the following full model:

Logistic regression assumptions

We check four standard assumptions:

  1. The outcome is binary.
  2. There is an approximately linear relationship between continuous predictors and the logit of the outcome.
  3. There are no excessively influential outliers.
  4. There is no severe multicollinearity among predictors.

The diagnostics suggest that:

  • The outcome is appropriately binary.
  • Plots of residuals vs.Â predictors do not indicate strong non-linearity.
  • There are no highly influential points with Cookâs distance > 0.5.
  • VIF values are low, indicating no serious multicollinearity.

Thus, logistic regression is a reasonable modelling choice for this dataset.

Three logistic regression models

Due to the relatively low prevalence of stroke in the dataset (about 5â6%), we consider three models:

  1. Baseline logistic regression
  2. Firthâs penalized logistic regression (reduces small-sample and separation bias)
  3. FLIC (Firth with intercept correction, aligning predicted event rate with observed prevalence)

Confusion matrix and performance measures

We evaluate the models using:

  • Confusion matrices (at a 0.5 threshold)
  • Precision, recall, F1 score
  • AUC (area under the ROC curve)
  • Youdenâs J statistic (for optimal threshold selection)

Future directions and conclusion

In this dataset, logistic regression performs well as a stroke classifier using commonly known risk factors (age, hypertension, heart disease, glucose, BMI, etc.). Firth and FLIC offer theoretical advantages in settings with severe imbalance or separation, but here they yield results very similar to the standard model.

Possible future directions include:

  • Exploring alternative models (e.g., random forests, gradient boosting, neural networks)
  • Using resampling or SMOTE to adjust class imbalance and comparing resulting performance
  • Performing external validation on a different stroke dataset
  • Investigating calibration (how well predicted probabilities align with observed risk)

Overall, logistic regression remains an interpretable and clinically useful method for stroke risk prediction in this setting.
